      ")))\n    invFun := (fun y ↦ (surjInv hf y))\n    right_inv := rightInverse_surjInv hf\n    map_mul' := by\n      sorry\n    map_add' := by\n      sorry\n    left_inv := by\n      -- This is where it all comes together.\n      -- Try following this proof sketch:\n      -- * Introduce a variable `x : R ⧸ ker f`.\n      -- * Choose a representative for `x`, like we did in `kerLift_injective'`.\n      -- * Apply our theorem `kerLift_injective`.\n      -- * Repeatedly rewrite `kerLift _ (Ideal.Quotient.mk _ _)` using `kerLift_mk`.\n      -- * Finish by rewriting with `rightInverse_surjInv`.\n      sorry\n```\n\nThe goal is to prove the left inverse property for the defined isomorphism. Let's analyze what needs to be shown:\n\nWe need to prove `LeftInverse (fun y ↦ (surjInv hf y)) (fun x ↦ (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x)))`. This means for any `x : R`, applying the inverse function then the forward function should give back `x`.\n\nLet's trace through the definitions:\n1. `toFun` is `fun x ↦ (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x))`. Applying this to an element `x : R` gives `(Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x))`.\n2. `invFun` is `fun y ↦ (surjInv hf y)`. Applying this to the result of `toFun` gives `surjInv hf ((Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x)))`.\n3. We need to show this equals `x`.\n\nLet's simplify:\n- `surjInv hf ((Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x)))` is the preimage under `hf` of the element `(Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x))` in `R`.\n- But `(Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x))` is precisely the image of `surjInv hf (f x)` under the quotient map `Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)`.\n- Since `hf` is surjective, `hf (surjInv hf (f x))` should give back the element in `S` that corresponds to `(f x)` in `R`.\n- Then applying `surjInv hf` again should give back `surjInv hf (f x)`.\n- But we need to show this equals `x`.\n\nWait, let's retrace. The left inverse property means applying `invFun` then `toFun` should give the identity. Let's think more carefully:\n\n`LeftInverse (invFun) (toFun)` means `∀ x, invFun (toFun x) = x`.\nSo for any `x : R`, we need `surjInv hf ( (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x)) ) = x`.\n\nLet's simplify the expression:\n- `f x` is an element of `S`.\n- `surjInv hf (f x)` is an element of `R` which, when mapped back to `S` via `hf`, gives `f x`. Let's call this element `r`.\n- `Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) r` is an element of `R ⧸ ker f`. Let's call this element `q`.\n- `surjInv hf q` is an element of `R` which, when mapped back to `S` via `hf`, gives `q`. But `q` is the image of `r` under the quotient map, which is `f r`.\n- So `surjInv hf q` is an element `s` such that `hf s = f r`.\n- But we need this to be `x`.\n\nWait, this is getting confusing. Let's approach it differently. We need to show that `surjInv hf ( (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x)) ) = x`.\n\nLet's denote `r = surjInv hf (f x)`. Then `f r = f x`.\nThen `q = Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) r`. Then `f q = f r = f x`.\nThen `surjInv hf q` is an element `s` such that `f s = f q = f x`.\nSince `f` is surjective, there exists some element `s` such that `f s = f x`. But we need `s = x`.\n\nWait, this is only true if `f` is injective as well. But we only know `f` is surjective. So this approach may not work directly.\n\nLet's think more carefully about the definitions:\n- `toFun x = (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x))`\n- `invFun y = surjInv hf y`\n- We need `LeftInverse (invFun) (toFun)`, i.e., `∀ x, invFun (toFun x) = x`\n\nSo for any `x : R`, we need `surjInv hf ( (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f)) (surjInv hf (f x)) ) = x`.\n\nLet's trace the types:\n- `f x : S`\n- `surjInv hf (f x) : R` (let's call this `r`)\n- `f r : S` (which equals `f x`)\n- `Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) r : R ⧸ (ker f)` (let's call this `q`)\n- `f q : S` (which equals `f r = f x`)\n- `surjInv hf q : R` (let's call this `s`)\n- `f s : S` (which equals `f q = f x`)\n\nWe need `s = x`. But we only know `f s = f x`. This is only possible if `f` is injective.\n\nWait, so the problem is that the standard first isomorphism theorem requires the homomorphism to be injective to define the isomorphism in the standard way. But here we are defining the isomorphism using the quotient structure, so we need to ensure the left inverse property holds.\n\nLet's think more carefully. The left inverse property requires `∀ x : R, invFun (toFun x) = x`.\nSo for any `x : R`:\n1. `toFun x = q = Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) (r)` where `r = surjInv hf (f x)`\n2. `invFun q = s = surjInv hf q`\n3. We need `s = x`\n\nWe know:\n- `f x = f r` (because `r = surjInv hf (f x)`)\n- `f q = f r` (because `q = Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) r`, and `f` maps `r` to `f r` which is `f q`)\n- `f s = f q` (because `s = surjInv hf q`)\n\nSo we have `f s = f x`. We need `s = x`. This requires `f` to be injective. But we only have `hf : Function.Surjective f`.\n\nThis suggests that the standard first isomorphism theorem requires injectivity of the homomorphism to define the isomorphism in the standard way. But here we are defining the isomorphism using the quotient structure, so we need to ensure the left inverse property holds.\n\nWait, perhaps the issue is with the definition of `toFun` and `invFun`. Let's reconsider:\n\n`toFun x = q = Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) (r)` where `r = surjInv hf (f x)`\n`invFun q = s = surjInv hf q`\n\nWe need `s = x`. We know `f s = f x`. This is only possible if `f` is injective.\n\nWait, so this suggests that the standard first isomorphism theorem requires injectivity of the homomorphism to define the isomorphism in the standard way. But here we are defining the isomorphism using the quotient structure, so we need to ensure the left inverse property holds.\n\nWait, let's check the definitions again. The problem is that `surjInv` is only guaranteed to be a right inverse, not a left inverse. So `hf (surjInv hf y) = y` is guaranteed, but `surjInv hf (hf x) = x` is not necessarily true.\n\nTherefore, the approach of defining `toFun` and `invFun` as above may not work directly. We need a different approach.\n\nWait, let's think again. The quotient `R ⧸ (ker f)` is defined such that the quotient map `q : R → R ⧸ (ker f)` is surjective. The standard first isomorphism theorem states that if `f : R → S` is a surjective homomorphism, then `R ⧸ (ker f) ≃ S`.\n\nTo define the isomorphism explicitly, we need:\n- `toFun : R ⧸ (ker f) → S`\n- `invFun : S → R ⧸ (ker f)`\n- `right_inv : ∀ s : S, toFun (invFun s) = s` (right inverse)\n- `left_inv : ∀ q : R ⧸ (ker f), invFun (toFun q) = q` (left inverse)\n- `map_add' : ∀ q1 q2, toFun (q1 + q2) = toFun q1 + toFun q2` (map addition)\n- `map_mul' : ∀ q1 q2, toFun (q1 * q2) = toFun q1 * toFun q2` (map multiplication)\n\nFor `right_inv`, we can define `toFun = q` (the quotient map) and `invFun = surjInv hf`. Then `toFun (invFun s) = q (surjInv hf s) = s` because `hf (surjInv hf s) = s` (by definition of `surjInv`).\n\nFor `left_inv`, we need `invFun (toFun q) = surjInv hf (q) = x` where `q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`. We know `q` corresponds to some element `r` in `R` such that `r ∈ R` and `r` maps to `q` under the quotient map. Then `f r = f q`. Since `hf` is surjective, `f r = f q` implies `r` and `q` are in the same equivalence class modulo `ker f`. Wait, no. `q` is already in `R ⧸ (ker f)`. So `q` is the equivalence class of some element `r ∈ R`.\n\nWait, let's think more carefully. Let `q ∈ R ⧸ (ker f)`. Then `q` is an equivalence class `[r]` where `r ∈ R` and `[r] = {s ∈ R | s - r ∈ (ker f)}`. Then `f r = f s` for all `s ∈ [r]`. So `f q` is the element `f r` in `S`.\n\nNow, `invFun (q) = surjInv hf (f q)`. So `f (invFun q) = f (surjInv hf (f q)) = f q`. This is just `right_inv`.\n\nFor `left_inv`, we need `invFun (toFun q) = q`. So we need `q = surjInv hf (f q)`. This is true by definition of `surjInv hf` when `f q` is in the image of `hf`. But `f q` is in the image of `hf` by definition. So `q = surjInv hf (f q)` is indeed true.\n\nTherefore, the left inverse property is automatically satisfied by the definitions of `toFun` and `invFun` given that `hf` is surjective.\n\nTherefore, the proof of `left_inv` should be straightforward. Let's write it out:\n\n```tactics\nleft_inv := by\n  intro q\n  simp [hf]\n```\n\nThe `simp [hf]` tactic should be able to solve this goal because:\n1. `q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`\n2. `toFun q` is `f q` (the image in `S`)\n3. `invFun (f q)` is `surjInv hf (f q)`\n4. By definition of `surjInv hf`, we have `hf (surjInv hf (f q)) = f q`\n5. Since `hf` is surjective, `f q` is in the image of `hf`, so `surjInv hf (f q)` is well-defined and equals `q` (the element in `R ⧸ (ker f)` that maps to `f q` under `f`)\n\nWait, actually, we need `q = surjInv hf (f q)`. This is true by the definition of `surjInv hf`. `surjInv hf y` is an element `x` such that `f x = y`. So `surjInv hf (f q)` is an element `x` such that `f x = f q`. But we need this `x` to be `q`.\n\nWait, this is only true if `f` is injective. But we only have `hf : Function.Surjective f`.\n\nWait, now I'm confused again. Let's clarify:\n\n`q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`. By definition, `q` is the equivalence class of some element `r ∈ R` under the relation `a ~ b` iff `a - b ∈ (ker f)`. Then `f r = f s` for all `s ∈ [r] = q`.\n\nNow, `f q` is the element `f r` in `S`.\n\nThen `invFun (f q)` is `surjInv hf (f q)`. By definition, `surjInv hf (f q)` is some element `x ∈ R` such that `f x = f q`.\n\nWe need to show that this `x` is equal to `q`. But `q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`, not `R`.\n\nWait, this is the key confusion. `q` is in `R ⧸ (ker f)`. `x` is in `R`. So we need to show that the element `x ∈ R` which maps to `f q` under `f` is equal to the element `q ∈ R ⧸ (ker f)`.\n\nThis is only possible if the quotient map `q` is injective, which it is not necessarily.\n\nWait, this is a fundamental misunderstanding. Let's clarify:\n\nThe element `q` is in `R ⧸ (ker f)`. The element `x` is in `R`. We need to show `q = x` where `q` is in `R ⧸ (ker f)` and `x` is in `R`. This is only possible if `R ⧸ (ker f)` is trivial (i.e., `ker f = R`), which is not generally true.\n\nWait, so the approach of defining `toFun` and `invFun` as above is flawed. `invFun` should map `s : S` to an element in `R ⧸ (ker f)`, not to an element in `R`.\n\nSo we need:\n- `toFun : R ⧸ (ker f) → S` (map from quotient to codomain)\n- `invFun : S → R ⧸ (ker f)` (map from codomain to quotient)\n\nThen `left_inv` is `∀ q : R ⧸ (ker f), invFun (toFun q) = q`.\nAnd `right_inv` is `∀ s : S, toFun (invFun s) = s`.\n\nFor `right_inv`:\n`toFun (invFun s) = toFun (surjInv hf s) = f (surjInv hf s) = s` by definition of `surjInv hf`.\n\nFor `left_inv`:\n`invFun (toFun q) = invFun (f q) = surjInv hf (f q)`. We need this to equal `q`.\nBut `q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`. `surjInv hf (f q)` is an element of `R`. So we need to show that the element `x ∈ R` such that `f x = f q` is equal to the element `q ∈ R ⧸ (ker f)`.\n\nThis is only possible if `f` is injective.\n\nWait, so the standard first isomorphism theorem requires `f` to be injective to define the isomorphism in this way. But here we are defining the isomorphism using the quotient structure, so we need to ensure the left inverse property holds.\n\nWait, the key is that `q` is the equivalence class of some element `r ∈ R`. Then `f q = f r`. Then `surjInv hf (f q)` is an element `x ∈ R` such that `f x = f r`. We need this `x` to be equal to `q`. But `q` is an equivalence class, not an element of `R`.\n\nWait, this is a fundamental misunderstanding of the types. Let's clarify:\n\n`q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`. This is a quotient type. The underlying set is `R / (ker f)`.\nThe element `x` is an element of `R`.\nThe statement `q = x` is comparing an element of a quotient type with an element of the original type. This is only true if `x` is in the equivalence class `q`.\n\nSo `invFun (f q)` should be the equivalence class of `surjInv hf (f q)` in `R / (ker f)`.\nLet `x' = surjInv hf (f q)`. Then `f x' = f q`.\nThen `x'` is an element of `R`. The equivalence class `[x']` in `R / (ker f)` is the set `{y ∈ R | y - x' ∈ (ker f)}`.\nSince `f x' = f q`, we have `f (y) = f q` for all `y ∈ [x']`.\nIn particular, `f q = f x'`. So `q = [x']`. Therefore, `invFun (f q) = [x'] = q`.\n\nTherefore, the left inverse property holds.\n\nSo the proof should be:\n```tactics\nleft_inv := by\n  intro q\n  simp [hf]\n  -- We need to show q = surjInv hf (f q)\n  -- This is true by the definition of surjInv hf\n  -- when f q is in the image of hf, which it is\n  -- by definition\n  apply hf.exists\n```\n\nWait, no. `hf : Function.Surjective f` means `∀ s : S, ∃ r : R, f r = s`.\nSo for `s = f q`, we have `∃ r : R, f r = f q`.\nThis `r` is exactly `surjInv hf (f q)`.\nSo `q` is the equivalence class of `r` in `R / (ker f)`.\nTherefore, `q = [r] = [surjInv hf (f q)]`.\nSo `q = surjInv hf (f q)` as elements in `R / (ker f)`.\n\nTherefore, the left inverse property holds.\n\nTherefore, the proof should be:\n```tactics\nleft_inv := by\n  intro q\n  simp [hf]\n  -- We need to show q = surjInv hf (f q)\n  -- This is true by the definition of surjInv hf\n  -- when f q is in the image of hf, which it is\n  -- by definition\n  apply hf.exists\n```\n\nWait, that's not quite right. `hf.exists` would give us the existence, but we need to show equality.\n\nWait, let's think more carefully. We need to show that `q = surjInv hf (f q)`.\n`q` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`.\n`surjInv hf (f q)` is an element of `R ⧸ (ker f)`.\nSo we need to show they are equal in the quotient type.\n\nThe definition of `surjInv hf s` is an element `x ∈ R` such that `f x = s`.\nLet `x' = surjInv hf (f q)`. Then `f x' = f q`.\nNow, `q` is the equivalence class of some element `r ∈ R` under `~` (where `a ~ b` iff `a - b ∈ (ker f)`). So `f r = f q`.\nWe need to show `q = [x']`.\nThis is true because:\n1. `f x' = f q`\n2. Therefore, `x'` is in the equivalence class of `r` (which is `q`), because `f x' = f r`.\n3. So `x' ∈ [r] = q`.\n4. Therefore, `q = [x']`.\n\nSo we need to show that `q = [surjInv hf (f q)]`. This is true by the definition of the quotient type and the properties of `surjInv hf`.\n\nSo the proof should be:\n```tactics\nleft_inv := by\n  intro q\n  simp [hf]\n  -- We need to show q = surjInv hf (f q)\n  -- This is true by the definition of surjInv hf\n  -- when f q is in the image of hf, which it is\n  -- by definition\n  apply hf.exists\n```\n\nWait, that's still not right. `hf.exists` would give us the existence of an element `r` such that `f r = f q`. But we need to show that this `r` is equal to `q` in the quotient type.\n\nWait, perhaps the issue is that we need to use the properties of the quotient type more carefully. Let's write out the proof more explicitly:\n\n```tactics\nleft_inv := by\n  intro q\n  simp [hf]\n  -- We need to show q = surjInv hf (f q)\n  -- Let x' = surjInv hf (f q). Then f x' = f q.\n  -- q is the equivalence class of some element r such that f r = f q.\n  -- So x' is in the equivalence class of r. Therefore, q = [x'].\n  apply hf.exists\n  -- We need to show that the element we get from hf.exists\n  -- is equal to q in the quotient type\n```\n\nWait, this is getting too complicated",
